T1  - United States concessions in the Kennedy Round and short-run labor adjustment costs
AU  - Cheh, John H.
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 4
IS  - 4
SP  - 323
EP  - 340
PY  - 1974
DA  - 1974/11/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(74)90014-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199674900142
AB  - This paper reports on an econometric analysis of the exemptions awarded to United States industries from the across-the-board 50 percent tariff cut imposed in the Kennedy Round. It is shown that as much as 50 percent of the inter-industry variation in reductions in nominal tariff and non-tariff rates may be accounted for by variables that proxy labor adjustment costs. In particular, certain industrial characteristics are significantly related to the Kennedy Round reductions: declining industries, and industries with a high proportion of unskilled or old workers, are associated with low reductions.
